# Typography

## Font stack

- **Sans (default):** Geist Sans → Noto Sans SC → system-ui / PingFang SC / Microsoft YaHei
- **Mono (nav / tool labels):** IBM Plex Mono → Noto Sans SC → ui-monospace
- Geist Sans loads **400 + 500 only** (no SemiBold). Do not introduce new font families without an explicit request.
- Prefer CSS vars: `var(--font-geist-sans)`, `var(--font-noto-sans-sc)`, `var(--font-ibm-plex-mono)`. Do not hardcode mono family names.

## Weights (only these)

| Weight | Use |
|--------|-----|
| **400** | Body, captions, muted copy, light headline segments |
| **500** | Titles, section labels, h1–h4, emphasis, buttons (incl. `.buttonSticker`) |

- Do **not** add `600`, `700`, or other weights in new CSS.
- Noto Sans SC is loaded at 400/500 only — heavier values fake-bold and look inconsistent across platforms.
- Always set `font-weight` on headings (`h1`–`h4`). Browser default bold is 700 and will look too heavy.
- Global baseline: `globals.css` sets `h1–h6 { font-weight: 500 }`. Override to `400` only for intentionally light segments. Never rely on the browser default.

## Patterns

- Section eyebrows: ~12–14px, weight 500, `uppercase`, letter-spacing ~0.08–0.12em
- Decision / design-point pills: weight 500, accent border + matching text color
- Body: ~15–16px, weight 400, line-height ~1.75–1.8
- Italic is OK for headline emphasis segments; do not use weight to fake emphasis when italic/color already does

## Checklist when editing type

1. New text styles use only 400 or 500
2. Headings explicitly set `font-weight: 500` (or 400 for intentionally light segments)
3. Chinese and English share the same weight scale
4. Mono only for nav / code-like UI chrome, not for case-study body copy
